            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Dayan\u2019s roots are Pomo, but his life was forged in the fog of San Francisco. His grandparents were part of the generation moved to the Bay Area under the Indian Relocation Act, trading reservation life for the promise of urban opportunity. Growing up in the Mission District of the 1970s, Kai learned resilience from his father, a union carpenter, and an appreciation for community from his mother, who worked at the Indian Center. He was a practical kid, more interested in taking apart a toaster to see how it worked than in schoolbooks.\n\nThis hands-on curiosity led him to a Construction Management program at City College. He loved the logic of systems and structures, but his formal education was cut short by the birth of his daughter, Maya. Prioritizing a steady paycheck, Kai took an entry-level maintenance job at a downtown firm. He didn't have the degree, but he had an intuitive understanding of buildings. Over two decades, his work ethic and problem-solving skills propelled him up the ladder, from technician to supervisor, and finally to Senior Facilities Manager for a prestigious scientific research company. He knows every inch of his high-rise\u2014from the HVAC system's deepest groans to the quirks of the emergency generators.\n\nNow 50 and amicably divorced, Kai lives in a modest but well-kept condo in the Inner Richmond he bought fifteen years ago. His daily routine is a bedrock of stability: the 5-Fulton Muni bus to his downtown office, a thermos of black coffee at his desk, and evenings spent cooking or FaceTiming with Maya, now a graphic designer in Portland. He sees a different San Francisco than the tourists or tech transplants; he sees the city's skeleton of steel, concrete, and wiring, a complex organism he helps keep alive.\n\nHis aspirations have shifted from personal advancement to legacy. He dreams of mentoring young people from backgrounds like his, showing them a path into the skilled trades. He hopes to one day take a long trip through Northern California to reconnect with the Pomo lands he knows only through family stories. For now, Kai finds contentment in his quiet, ordered life\u2014a man who understands that the true foundation of a city, and a life, is built not of grand visions, but of careful, daily maintenance."
        },
