            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, the air thick with sawdust in a Mission district kitchen his father was remodeling. His dad handed him the brass plumb bob, its weight solid in his small hand. \"This doesn't lie, Kai,\" he'd said, showing him how the string found its perfect, unwavering vertical line. It wasn't about grades or books; it was about gravity, about what was real and true. That's the moment Kai understood that knowing how things *worked* was a different, more honest kind of intelligence.\n\n2.\nHe was thirteen when his mother pulled a small, tightly woven Pomo basket from a cedar box. \"Your great-grandmother made this,\" she said, her voice soft. He ran his thumb over the intricate geometric patterns, the texture so different from the concrete and metal of his world. It was a piece of a life he\u2019d never lived, a story from the land his family left behind. It rooted him in a history deeper than the city's foundations, a quiet ache of belonging he still carries.\n\n3.\nThe City College blueprints felt flimsy and distant the first time he held Maya. She was just a few hours old, a warm, solid weight against his chest in the quiet of the hospital ward. The whir of the HVAC system was a low hum in the background. In that moment, his ambition didn't collapse; it simply solidified into a new form. His future was no longer a grand design to be drafted, but a life to be built, beam by steady beam, for her.\n\n4.\nHe was in his late twenties, still new on the job, when the entire high-rise went dark. A transformer had blown. While managers barked into phones, Kai headed for the basement with a flashlight. He felt the building's silence, its sudden lack of breath. Tracing schematics in his mind, he bypassed the fried connection to a backup generator. When the emergency lights flickered on, the silence was replaced by a hum he understood. It was the first time he knew, truly knew, he belonged there.\n\n5.\nThe first night in his Inner Richmond condo, he didn\u2019t unpack. Kai just sat on the floor, listening. There were no upstairs neighbors' footsteps, no landlord's rules. For the first time, the sounds\u2014the groan of the pipes, the whisper of fog against the window, the distant rumble of the 5-Fulton\u2014belonged to him. At thirty-five, after a life of renting, the feeling wasn\u2019t excitement, but a deep, settling quiet. He had finally built a small, solid piece of the city for himself."
